  "prompt": "What are the best books/Tutorials to learn C# for non-beginners programmers?",
  "response": "If you are already familiar with programming concepts and want to deepen your understanding of C#, there are several books and resources that can help you advance your skills:\n\n1. **\"C# in Depth\" by Jon Skeet** - This book is highly recommended for developers who already have some experience with C#. It delves into the more complex features of the language and is an excellent resource for understanding the intricacies of modern C#.\n\n2. **\"Pro C# 10 with .NET 6\" by Andrew Troelsen and Philip Japikse** - This book provides an in-depth look at C# 10 and .NET 6, offering a comprehensive guide that covers advanced topics and industry best practices.\n\n3. **\"CLR via C#\" by Jeffrey Richter** - Although it may not be the newest book, it provides deep insights into how C# works with the Common Language Runtime, which can be invaluable for advanced developers.\n\n4. **\"C# Programming Yellow Book\" by Rob Miles** - While initially aimed at beginners, many have found that the later sections provide valuable insights even for experienced programmers.\n\n5. **\"The C# Player\u2019s Guide\" by RB Whitaker** - This is a great resource that progresses from basic to advanced topics and is often praised for its clear explanations and practical approach.\n\n6. **Pluralsight Courses** - Pluralsight offers a wide range of advanced C# courses taught by industry experts. These courses can help with keeping up to date with the latest C# features and best practices.\n\n7. **Microsoft's C# Documentation** - The official documentation is an excellent resource for advanced learners wanting to understand the latest features and syntax.\n\n8. **YouTube Channels and Online Tutorials** - Channels like Tim Corey, Mosh Hamedani, and Nick Chapsas provide more dynamic and visual forms of learning C#, focusing on advanced topics and real-world applications.\n\nWhen choosing resources, it\u2019s helpful to look for those that match your learning style, whether you prefer structured books, interactive courses, or video tutorials.",
